Movie Database Project

Welcome to the Movie Database Project! This project involves managing a movie database with various SQL queries and operations using SQLite and Node.js.

Table of Contents

Project Overview
Installation
Usage
Features
Contributing
License
Project Overview

This project is designed to handle a movie database where you can:

Query for movies based on different criteria.
Manage movie ratings and information.
Perform advanced SQL operations and handle transactions using Node.js.
Installation

Prerequisites
Node.js (v14 or higher)
SQLite3
Setup
Clone the Repository:
bash
Copy code
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/moviedatabaseproject.git
cd moviedatabaseproject
Install Dependencies:
bash
Copy code
npm install
Database Setup:
Make sure you have an SQLite database named movies.db in the project directory. If not, you can create it using the provided schema or SQL scripts.
Usage

Running SQL Queries
To execute queries, you can use SQLite3 directly or integrate with Node.js scripts.

Node.js Scripts
The project includes a Node.js script that allows you to add a movie to the database.

Add a Movie:
bash
Copy code
node handleMovieCLI.js "Movie Title" 2023
This script checks if the movie already exists. If not, it adds the movie with default values for rating and votes.
Features

Basic SQL Queries: Run simple SELECT queries to retrieve data.
Data Manipulation: Insert, update, and delete movie records.
Advanced SQL: Use JOINs, subqueries, and aggregate functions to analyze movie data.
Node.js Integration: Handle database operations and transactions via Node.js scripts.
Contributing

If you would like to contribute to this project, please follow these steps:

Fork the Repository:
Click the "Fork" button on the top-right of the repository page.
Create a Feature Branch:
bash
Copy code
git checkout -b feature/your-feature
Commit Your Changes:
bash
Copy code
git add .
git commit -m "Add your message here"
Push to Your Fork:
bash
Copy code
git push origin feature/your-feature
Create a Pull Request:
Go to the original repository and click "New Pull Request." Select your branch and submit the pull request.
